{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c3fc5e23-bacf-4b13-a934-e7861af21feb","content":"## What happened\n\nApple's Security.framework **does not implement DSA**. In earlier .NET versions, macOS silently fell back to an OpenSSL-based provider for DSA operations. In .NET 11, that fallback was removed — `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS (and iOS/tvOS).\n\nDSA has been on the deprecation path for a while (`SYSLIB0017` obsoletions were added in .NET 7).\n\n## How to fix\n\nSince you only need to **verify** legacy signatures, the cleanest cross-platform fix is to use **BouncyCastle's managed DSA implementation**, which doesn't depend on any OS crypto provider:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\nThen replace the `System.Security.Cryptography.DSA` calls:\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\npublic static bool VerifyLegacyDsa(byte[] publicKeyBytes, byte[] data, byte[] signature)\n{\n    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\n    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\"); // match your original hash\n    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);\n    verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\n    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\n## Long-term recommendation\n\nDSA is considered legacy. Plan a migration to **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** for new signatures, and keep the BouncyCastle path only for verifying old data that can't be re-signed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8efd654d-3349-41de-8449-2895db33650a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this from my knowledge.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, and more significantly in later versions, Microsoft has been deprecating and removing older cryptographic algorithms. Specifically:\n\nIn .NET 7+, DSA on macOS was never natively supported by Apple's security frameworks. The DSA implementation on macOS relied on OpenSSL via the `System.Security.Cryptography` package. \n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nThe core issue is that Apple's native crypto libraries don't support DSA, and .NET on macOS historically used OpenSSL as a fallback for DSA operations. In later .NET versions, Microsoft removed that OpenSSL dependency on macOS, which means DSA is no longer available on Apple platforms. This would explain why the user is seeing failures after upgrading to .NET 11. throwing `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS since at least .NET 5 when Apple's native crypto APIs replaced OpenSSL. So if the user's code worked in .NET 10 but broke in .NET 11, it's likely a deliberate removal or stricter enforcement of DSA support across all platforms, not just macOS. For verification of legacy DSA signatures, I could use BouncyCastle which has its own managed implementation, or depend on OpenSSL explicitly on macOS. The long-term solution would be migrating to modern algorithms like ECDSA or Ed25519. Given Microsoft's trajectory of removing DSA support on platforms where native crypto providers don't support it, macOS is likely the first to lose this capability.","outputTokens":1732,"requestId":"B41E:39B23B:913B58:B30390:6A0135BF"},"id":"54f29569-6955-4e4a-a25b-f3c4c0a8fcf0","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:50:29.344Z","parentId":"22c7f303-0d7f-48d1-bf4b-3a45889a28c6"}
